      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789237#p40789237" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">EspressoMachine</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Honestly the whole Hawking radiation analogy made no sense to me. If matter and anti-matter meet it will destroy itself and release energy. But in the analogy seems like it has a destructive force that makes the whole thing vanish out of existence. It's confusing.</div><br />AIUI, there's no energetic annihilation because the pair of particles borrows energy in order to pop into existence, and the energy is repaid when they meet. Or something. The analogy has never made any sense to me either.<br /><br />Unfortunately, the non-analogy version is so <a href="https://physics.stackexchange.com/questions/251385/an-explanation-of-hawking-radiation" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">gobsmackingly confusing</a> that it's more or less useless to even try understanding it without a firm grounding in quantum field theory. So virtual particles it is!
      
