      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789237#p40789237" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">EspressoMachine</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789208#p40789208" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">pokrface</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789156#p40789156" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Sekhmet</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Can we please stop affirming that black holes have &quot;singularities&quot; in them, as if we knew that is what's actually going on inside inside of them?</div><br />It's a succinct way of describing a black hole's innards without having to write an entire primer on quantum field theory (which I am utterly unqualified to do). And Hawking radiation isn't really virtual particles popping in and out of existence either, but that's the commonly presented analogy for that, too.<br /><br />If this were an academic paper instead of a fun and informative video for laypersons, I guess I'd be a lot picker about terminology. But it ain't, so I'm not. ¯\_(ツ)_/¯</div><br />Honestly the whole Hawking radiation analogy made no sense to me. If matter and anti-matter meet it will destroy itself and release energy. But in the analogy seems like it has a destructive force that makes the whole thing vanish out of existence. It's confusing.</div><br /><br /><br />Hawking called it a &quot;heuristic&quot;, but it's more about getting the numbers to add up rather than an intuitive model.
      
