    <span class="author" data-post-author="madmax559"><a href="/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&u=221201" rel="nofollow">madmax559</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Legatus Legionis</span><a class="subscriber" href="/store/product/subscriptions/">et Subscriptor</a>
      <aside class="icons">
        
          <a href="?comments=1&amp;post=40789414&amp;mode=quote#reply" class='quotelink icon' rel='nofollow' title="Reply">reply</a>
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2022/03/exploring-the-counterintuitive-mysteries-of-black-holes-with-paul-sutter/?comments=1&post=40789414#comment-40789414" title="2022-03-30T15:25:18+00:00" class="timeago datetime" rel="nofollow">Wed Mar 30, 2022 10:25 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789252#p40789252" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">pokrface</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789237#p40789237" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">EspressoMachine</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Honestly the whole Hawking radiation analogy made no sense to me. If matter and anti-matter meet it will destroy itself and release energy. But in the analogy seems like it has a destructive force that makes the whole thing vanish out of existence. It's confusing.</div><br />AIUI, there's no energetic annihilation because the pair of particles borrows energy in order to pop into existence, and the energy is repaid when they meet. Or something. The analogy has never made any sense to me either.<br /><br />Unfortunately, the non-analogy version is so <a href="https://physics.stackexchange.com/questions/251385/an-explanation-of-hawking-radiation" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">gobsmackingly confusing</a> that it's more or less useless to even try understanding it without a firm grounding in quantum field theory. So virtual particles it is!</div><br /><br />The easiest way to visualize this is to think of this in terms of energy fields or bedsheets, except that the field is all permeating &amp; around us &amp; the bedsheet is hanging from a clothesline<br /><br />Stick a finger in the bedsheet &amp; it deforms on the other side.  Reverse this &amp; you have a new structure on your side<br /><br />This was the first thing that came to mind in my undergrad physics class studying the above ....<br /><br />Therefore &quot;We are all walking deformations on the bedsheet of reality&quot;<br /><br /><img class="ars-emoticon" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/styles/images/smilies/big_grin.png" alt=":D" title="Big Green" />
      
    </div>
    <footer>
      <span class="userinfo">11385 posts | reg. <time class="reg-date">Aug 25, 2009</time></span>
    </footer>
