        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/science/2022/03/exploring-the-counterintuitive-mysteries-of-black-holes-with-paul-sutter/?comments=1&post=40789916#comment-40789916" title="2022-03-30T17:30:52+00:00" class="timeago datetime" rel="nofollow">Wed Mar 30, 2022 12:30 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789252#p40789252" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">pokrface</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="https://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=40789237#p40789237" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">EspressoMachine</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Honestly the whole Hawking radiation analogy made no sense to me. If matter and anti-matter meet it will destroy itself and release energy. But in the analogy seems like it has a destructive force that makes the whole thing vanish out of existence. It's confusing.</div><br />AIUI, there's no energetic annihilation because the pair of particles borrows energy in order to pop into existence, and the energy is repaid when they meet. Or something. The analogy has never made any sense to me either.<br /><br />Unfortunately, the non-analogy version is so <a href="https://physics.stackexchange.com/questions/251385/an-explanation-of-hawking-radiation" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">gobsmackingly confusing</a> that it's more or less useless to even try understanding it without a firm grounding in quantum field theory. So virtual particles it is!</div><br /><br />I think Paul McCartney got it right when he wrote a song (the worst song he ever wrote) which included the words, &quot;Joan was quizzical, studied Pataphysical Science in the home&quot;.  <br /><br />One definition of 'pataphysics is that it's &quot;a branch of philosophy or science that examines imaginary phenomena that exist in a world beyond metaphysics; it is the science of imaginary solutions.&quot; <br /><br />Bang, bang
      
    </div>
